#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:22
msgid "You're doing well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:23
msgid "*What can I do to improve?*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:24
msgid ""
"Enjoy the moment. Then, also ask for corrective feedback: \"What could "
"have been even better?\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:25
msgid "none"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:26
msgid "relieved"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:27
msgid "You are probably doing badly and no-one realises or cares."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:28
msgid "*Why is no-one paying attention to what I'm doing?*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:29
msgid "Go looking for feedback, urgently and persistently. Act on it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:30
msgid "negative"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:31
msgid "dismayed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:32
msgid ""
"You need to improve, but there's someone there to help you, who is paying"
" attention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:33
msgid "*At least I know what I should focus on.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:34
msgid ""
"Ensure you understand what is missing; work to provide it; ask for more "
"feedback on it as soon as you can."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:38
msgid "The risk of no feedback"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:40
msgid ""
"Someone who is new to a workplace or role quite can quite naturally feel "
"a strong need to fit in. When it's also an unfamiliar culture, with "
"unfamiliar expectations, it can feel very important to know that you are "
"meeting those expectations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:42
msgid ""
"There's nothing wrong or problematic about this in itself, but it's very "
"easy to take another, false, step."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:44
msgid ""
"You want to make a good impression, and you certainly don't want to find "
"out that you're doing things wrong."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:46
msgid ""
"It's tempting then to think that *not* getting corrective feedback, not "
"being questioned or challenged, is a good sign. It might feel safer not "
"to be noticed or have your work scrutinised. You might think: \"No news "
"is good news; if no-one is picking me up on my work it means it's OK!\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:48
msgid ""
"**It is not OK and it is not a good sign.** It just means that you're not"
" being noticed, *which is disastrous for you*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:52
msgid "The conspiracy of inaction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:54
msgid ""
"If your performance at work is not being challenged or questioned, it's "
"probably not because you are meeting expectations well. It's more likely "
"that *it's easier for everyone not to do anything about it*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:58
msgid "It's human nature to take the easy way out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:62
msgid "Other people are disinclined to act"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:64
msgid ""
"If you are making a visible, spectacular, unignorable mess of things, "
"someone will have to do something about it. But otherwise, the temptation"
" is for other people not to confront it, even if it's not up to the "
"required standard."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:66
msgid ""
"They will tell themselves that your substandard performance is not an "
"urgent matter. They will ignore it in the hope that it will rectify "
"itself. They'll say to themselves: \"There's plenty of time - if it's not"
" looking better by next week, we can have a proper look at it then.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:68
msgid ""
"It takes a lot of energy, intellectual and emotional, to apply a course "
"correction to someone else."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:72
msgid "*You* will be disinclined to act"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:74
msgid ""
"At the same time, for the person whose work is at risk of not meeting "
"standards, it's also easier to do nothing, to stay quiet, and to keep "
"their head down. If you're not completely sure that everything you're "
"doing is up to scratch, why risk drawing attention to it? By next week "
"you might have it figured out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:76
msgid ""
"And so on. Nobody wants to bring a problem to the surface. Everybody "
"hopes it will go away. Everyone will look for the easy, uncomplicated "
"path. It's like a conspiracy of inaction. Every human instinct combines "
"to prevent a confrontation with underperformance - and then suddenly one "
"day it will be unavoidable, and quite possibly, **too late to save the "
"day**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:78
msgid ""
"Nobody *wanted* that to happen, but it's a risk that creeps up on you, "
"cunningly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:82
msgid "Crisis and survival mode thinking"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:84
msgid ""
"When things get bad, a person who is anxious about how they're doing is "
"likely to go into *survival mode*, in which getting through the day "
"without having faced difficult questions or critical comment feels like a"
" kind of success. Of course you can avoid getting negative feedback by "
"avoiding *any* feedback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:86
msgid ""
"Now you really are locked into a spiral of doom. It's amazing how "
"effectively someone who fears feedback can avoid or delay receiving it, "
"mostly through unconscious strategies and the signals they give out to "
"other people. It's hard enough for many to give negative feedback in the "
"first place. Someone who is actively avoiding it - even without realising"
" that that is what they are doing - is likely to crash, without ever "
"having reached out for the one thing that could help them, all the while "
"telling themselves that they are surviving."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:88
msgid ""
"Asking for feedback can be a terribly hard thing to do when you already "
"sense that things aren't going well, but it is the first and necessary "
"step to get yourself out of survival mode thinking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:92
msgid "Feedback on *good* performance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:94
msgid ""
"On the converse side, if you are doing well, **you need your good "
"performance to be seen, and you still need feedback on it**. It's not "
"good enough to be doing the right things, unnoticed and unremarked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:96
msgid ""
"You need feedback and insight, so that you know *what* you're doing "
"right, and *why* it's right and *how* to keep on doing it right."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:98
msgid ""
"Work that represents an excellent start for someone in a junior position "
"will not be adequate for the same person once they are settled in; you "
"need to keep raising the quality and value of your work. That requires a "
"lot more than the occasional nod of approval from a senior. It requires "
"active, close engagement, with multiple people, who are able to give your"
" work real attention, thought and time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:100
msgid ""
"Once again the conspiracy of inaction can creep up on you here. Someone "
"starts well, gets good feedback and continues sailing along happily. But "
"the expectations don't remain the same, and neither you nor the people "
"around you will notice immediately if you begin to fall short of them. "
"Now, alarm bells should be ringing if you're not getting feedback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:102
msgid ""
"To know that things are going well, you need to be getting positive "
"feedback. At least you should be getting corrective feedback, so that you"
" know people are still paying attention to you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:106
msgid "Make sure you get feedback"
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:108
msgid ""
"**Make getting feedback normal and expected, from the very beginning.** "
"Don't wait for it to come. It might not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:110
msgid ""
"Record it, so you know that you are getting it, from who and how much. It"
" will also help you see patterns that show where you need to turn your "
"attention, but the point here is simply to ensure that you are getting "
"feedback - that others are noticing your work, and caring about it and "
"about you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:112
msgid ""
"Normalising it also helps make it easier for you to get feedback when it "
"really matters, when it's going to help you, and makes receiving "
"feedback, even the dreaded negative feedback, easier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../getting-feedback.rst:116
msgid ""
"Getting feedback is crucial - but you also need to :ref:`deal with "
"feedback effectively <dealing-with-feedback>`."
msgstr ""

